04541nam a22007335i 9780674919419DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20182018mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806749194197 a10.4159/97806749194192doi  a(DE-B1597)500399  a(OCoLC)1054879336  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKF1262 7aLAW0600002bisacsh04a342.7308581 aZiegler, Mary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond Abortion :b‹i›Roe v. Wade‹/i› and the Battle for Privacy /cMary Ziegler. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (350 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tA History of Privacy Politics -- tSexual Liberty -- tMental Illness and the Right to Refuse Treatment -- tDeregulation and the Future of Medicine -- tDeath, Discrimination, and Equality -- tConscientious Objection, Roe, and the Role of the Judiciary -- tConclusion -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor most Americans today, Roe v. Wade concerns just one thing: the right to choose abortion. But the Supreme Court’s decision once meant much more. The justices ruled that the right to privacy encompassed the abortion decision. Grassroots activists and politicians used Roe—and popular interpretations of it—as raw material in answering much larger questions: Is there a right to privacy? For whom, and what is protected? As Mary Ziegler demonstrates, Roe’s privacy rationale attracted a wide range of citizens demanding social changes unrelated to abortion. Movements questioning hierarchies based on sexual orientation, profession, class, gender, race, and disability drew on Roe to argue for an autonomy that would give a voice to the vulnerable. So did advocates seeking expanded patient rights and liberalized euthanasia laws. Right-leaning groups also invoked Roe’s right to choose, but with a different agenda: to attack government involvement in consumer protection, social welfare, racial justice, and other aspects of American life. In the 1980s, seeking to unify a fragile coalition, the Republican Party popularized the idea that Roe was a symbol of judicial tyranny, discouraging anyone from relying on the decision to frame their demands. But Beyond Abortion illuminates the untapped potential of arguments that still resonate today. By recovering the diversity of responses to Roe, and the legal and cultural battles it energized, Ziegler challenges readers to come to terms with the uncomfortable fact that privacy belongs to no party or cause.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aMental health lawszUnited States. 0aPrivacy, Right ofzUnited States. 0aSexual freedomzUnited States. 0aTerminal carexLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aLAW / Legal History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674919419?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674919419423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674919419/original  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK